"level."
msgstr ""

#: src/1925-optional-match-vert.md:36
msgid "`F#` Context"
msgstr ""

#: src/1925-optional-match-vert.md:38
msgid ""
"In `F#`, enumerations (called `unions`) are declared in the following "
"fashion where all of these are equivalent:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1925-optional-match-vert.md:41
msgid ""
"```F#\n"
"// Normal union\n"
"type IntOrBool = I of int | B of bool\n"
"// For consistency, have all lines look the same\n"
"type IntOrBool = \n"
"   | I of int\n"
"   | B of bool\n"
"// Collapsing onto a single line is allowed\n"
"type IntOrBool = | I of int | B of bool\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/1925-optional-match-vert.md:52
msgid ""
"Their `match` statements adopt a similar style to this. Note that every `|` "
"is aligned, something which is not possible with current Rust:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1925-optional-match-vert.md:55
msgid ""
"```F#\n"
"match foo with\n"
"    | I -> \"\"\n"
"    | B -> \"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

